 Scheme -- tAppendix 11 Priests’ Burials from Medieval English Parish Churches and Hospitals -- tAppendix 12 Grave Goods Associated with Aged Skeletons from Medieval English Parish Churches and Hospitals -- tAppendix 13 The Classification of Grave Goods from Medieval Burials -- tAppendix 14 Infant Burials from Domestic Contexts in Medieval England -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aAn examination of daily life in the Middle Ages which reveals the intimate relations between age groups, between the living and the dead, and between people and things.An important and timely volume. an elegant summary of complex theory, and synthesis of an impressive body of material. It will be eagerly read by current and future generations of archaeologists, and will demonstrate the significance of historical archaeology to a much wider scholarly audience. Dr Kate Giles, University of York. The aim of this book is to explore how medieval life was actually lived - how people were born and grew old, how they dressed, how they inhabited their homes, the rituals that gave meaning to their lives and how they prepared for death and the afterlife. Its fresh and original approach uses archaeological evidence to reconstruct the material practices of medieval life, death and the afterlife. Previous historical studies of the medieval "lifecycle" begin with birth and end with death. Here, in contrast, the concept of life course theory is developed for the first time in a detailed archaeological case study. The author argues that medieval Christian understanding of the "life course" commenced with conception and extended through the entirety of life, to include death and the afterlife. Five thematic case studies present the archaeology of medieval England (c.1050-1540 CE) in terms of the body, the household, the parish church and cemetery, and the relationship between the lives of people and objects.A wide range of sources is critically employed: osteology, costume, material culture, iconography and evidence excavated from houses, churches and cemeteries in the medieval English town and countryside. Medieval Life reveals theintimate and everyday relations between age groups, between the living and the dead, and between people and things. Roberta Gilchrist is Professor of Archaeology at the University of Reading.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Apr 2024) 0aArchaeology, Medieval. 0aExcavations (Archaeology). 4aArchaeology & Heritage. 4aMedieval History. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Archaeology.2bisacsh  aAfterlife.  aAge Groups.  aArchaeology.  aChristian Understanding.  aDaily Life.  aDeath.  aLife Course.  aMaterial Practices.  aMedieval Life.  aMiddle Ages.  aPeople and Things.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertBoydell and Brewer Complete eBook-Package pre 2013z978311143139040uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978184615974940uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781846159749423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781846159749/original  a978-3-11-143139-0  Boydell and Brewer Complete eBook-Package pre 2013b2013  aGBV-deGruyter-alles